        <div class="container d-flex align-items-center justify-content-center">
            <div id="content" class="w-75">
                <div class="p-3 lang_info">
                    <% if (lang == 'c') { %>
                    <img src="img/C_Programming_Language.svg" alt="C programming language logo" width="100">
                    C is a general-purpose language created by Dennis Ritchie at Bell Labs in 1972 that has become one of the most influential programming languages, forming the foundation for many modern languages. It combines procedural and structured programming approaches with the ability to execute quickly and access hardware directly. C remains the go-to choice for building operating systems, embedded systems, compilers, and other system software. geeksforgeeks
                    The language sees extensive use across diverse domains: operating systems like Linux and UNIX, microcontrollers and IoT devices, device drivers and system utilities, database engines, game engines, network protocols and servers, desktop applications, scientific computing, and cybersecurity tools. <a href="https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/c/c-language-introduction/">source</a> 
                    <% } else if (lang == 'js') { %>
                    <img src="img/JavaScript.png" alt="javascript logo" width="100">
                    JavaScript is a lightweight, cross-platform programming language built to create dynamic web content. It runs on the client side in browsers where it works alongside HTML and CSS to make web pages interactive—enabling user interactions like button clicks, form submissions, and animations. JavaScript also powers server-side development through Node.js, where it handles database access, file operations, and server responses. geeksforgeeks
The language is in high demand across frontend, backend, and full-stack roles. Its ecosystem includes powerful frameworks like React, Angular, and Vue.js on the frontend, and Express.js and Node.js on the backend, making it essential for modern web development. JavaScript uses object-oriented and event-driven programming paradigms and runs natively in all modern browsers without requiring installation. geeksforgeeks
Applications range widely: building interactive websites, cross-platform mobile apps with React Native, browser-based games, server-side APIs, form validation and scripting, web scraping, IoT control systems, and real-time features like live chat and notifications using WebSockets. <a href="https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/javascript/javascript-tutorial/">source</a>
                    <% } else if (lang == 'rust') { %>
                    <img src="img/rust-programming-language-icon.webp" alt="rust language logo" width="100">
                    Rust offers static type checking that catches errors at compile time rather than runtime. Unlike many statically-typed languages, it uses optional types that force programmers to explicitly handle missing values, preventing null reference errors before code reaches users. For developers transitioning from garbage-collected languages, Rust's precise memory management delivers dramatic performance gains—one production user reduced memory usage from 5GB to 50MB by rewriting components in Rust. stackoverflow
Compared to C and C++, Rust's borrow checker eliminates entire categories of memory safety bugs by ensuring references don't outlive their data. Rust also provides zero-cost abstractions, allowing clean, high-level code that performs as well as handwritten low-level code. The ecosystem includes built-in tools like Cargo for dependency management and testing, and a welcoming community with strong documentation and conferences worldwide. stackoverflow
                    Rust offers static type checking that catches errors at compile time rather than runtime. Unlike many statically-typed languages, it uses optional types that force programmers to explicitly handle missing values, preventing null reference errors before code reaches users. For developers transitioning from garbage-collected languages, Rust's precise memory management delivers dramatic performance gains—one production user reduced memory usage from 5GB to 50MB by rewriting components in Rust. 
Downsides include a steep learning curve—the compiler's strict checks and requirement to handle all edge cases can be frustrating. Rapid prototyping is challenging compared to dynamic languages, some desired libraries may still be in development, and platform support is more limited than C or C++. <a href="https://stackoverflow.blog/2020/01/20/what-is-rust-and-why-is-it-so-popular/">source</a>
